Defendant John C Weichman in court with attorney Kiley Beth Zellner.  Defendant John C Weichman in custody.  Benjamin Lindsay appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy Court Clerk: dds.

Matter before the Court for continuation of Sentencing hearing.  Sentencing proceeded.  
 
AS TO COUNT 1:  The Court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM TERM OF IMPRISONMENT of 4 YEARS, CONSECUTIVE to any other time being served.  Credit time to be determined as the state objects to credit form submitted by defense.  The INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT in the Wisconsin State Prison System is 2 YEARS.  The MAXIMUM TERM OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION IS 2 YEARS.

The defendant IS NOT eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program.  The defendant IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program AFTER SERVING THE FIRST YEAR OF THIS SENTENCE.  

The Court STAYED this sentence and placed the defendant on probation for a period of 3 YEARS with the following conditions.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
*Serve 10 months in the House of Corrections with Huber release for medical care/treatment.  Electronic monitoring not prohibited by the Court.  If Electronic monitoring is granted the Court will allow release for attorney contacts, court appearances, and grocery shopping.  
*Referral for Mental health assessment and if necessary complete follow-up care/treatment;
*Take any prescribed medication only in the manner/dosage as prescribed by a treating physician;
*Obtain AODA assessment and complete follow-up care/treatment;
*Absolute sobriety (no drugs or alcohol) with random urine screens and breathalyzer tests;
*No illegal drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers/houses);
*Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent;
*No new law violations rising to the level of probable cause;
*Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school with part time employment;
*Pay all supervision fees;
*Provide DNA sample- pay surcharge;

The Court ordered defendant to pay a fine of $1200.00 plus all mandatory costs, penalties, surcharges, including $50.00 ignition interlock surcharge by the end of probation period- any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment- bail to apply. Court ordered AODA assessment and Driver's Safety Plan; cooperate with any treatment recommended.  Court ordered defendant's driving privileges revoked for a period of 3 years.  Court ordered defendant restricted to operation of vehicles equipped with an ignition interlock device for 24 months.  If revoked, the Court ordered that all financial obligations be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of funds under Sec. 973.05(4)(b) and as a condition of extended supervision.  Any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.  Defendant is informed he may not possess and/or own any firearms.  Defendant is informed he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been reinstated.  Appeal rights given by the court. 
Filed;
